    <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
      <body>
        <div rend="parallel">
          <p xml:id="Aink421-kilavi">viṉai palavaṟṟiṟkum pirintoḻukum talaimakaṉ piṉpu maṉaivayiṉ nīṅkātu oḻukukiṉṟa kātal uṇarntōr colliyatu.</p>
          <p xml:lang="en">Those who perceived the love that was the hero, whose conduct is to separate for all the many tasks, conducting [himself] without leaving the house, spoke [this].</p>
            </div>
        
        <div rend="parallel">
          <lg xml:id="Aink421">        
            <l>mālai veṇkāḻ kāvalar vīca</l>
            <l>naṟumpūm puṟavi ṉoṭuṅkumuya liriyum</l>
            <l>puṉpula nāṭaṉ maṭamaka</l>
            <l>ṇalaṅkiḷar paṇaittōḷ vilaṅkiṉa celavē.</l>
          </lg>
          <lg xml:lang="en">

<l>The bamboo shoulders that shine with goodness of the naive daughter</l>
<l>of the lord of that wasteland, where hiding<note xml:lang="ta-Latn" place="foot">What is the exact sense of <q xml:lang="ta-Latn"><hi rend="italic">oṭuṅku</hi></q>? Are the hares in the process of hiding, or is it in their nature to hide, in which case one might more appropriately translate 'shy hares'. Another alternative considered is that they are 'restrained (in their senses)', which one could streatch to being 'calm', or even 'lazy'.</note> hares retreat</l>
<l>into the woodland of fragrant flowers</l>
    <l>as the guards throw their short white sticks<note xml:lang="ta-Latn" place="foot">The TL cites this poem to support its definition of <q xml:lang="ta-Latn"><hi rend="italic">veṇkāḻ</hi></q> as 'small stick'. I am not quite clear how one arrives there etymologically -- presumably this is a lexicalisation of <foreign xml:lang="ta-Latn">veṇ</foreign> ('white') and <foreign xml:lang="ta-Latn">kāḻ</foreign> ('kernal, core'). Contextually, 'small stick' makes perfect sense.</note> the evening,</l> 
    <l>stopped his departure.</l>
</lg>
        </div>
      </body>
    </text>
